{"id":"1908.04551","submitter":"DaWei Yang","authors":"Yan-Quan Feng, Istv\\'an Kov\\'acs, Jie Wang, Da-Wei Yang","title":"Existence of non-Cayley Haar graphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A Cayley graph of a group $H$ is a finite simple graph $\\Gamma$ such that its\nautomorphism group ${\\rm Aut}(\\Gamma)$ contains a subgroup isomorphic to $H$\nacting regularly on $V(\\Gamma)$, while a Haar graph of $H$ is a finite simple\nbipartite graph $\\Sigma$ such that ${\\rm Aut}(\\Sigma)$ contains a subgroup\nisomorphic to $H$ acting semiregularly on $V(\\Sigma)$ and the $H$-orbits are\nequal to the partite sets of $\\Sigma$. It is well-known that every Haar graph\nof finite abelian groups is a Cayley graph. In this paper, we prove that every\nfinite non-abelian group admits a non-Cayley Haar graph except the dihedral\ngroups $D_6$, $D_8$, $D_{10}$, the quaternion group $Q_8$ and the group\n$Q_8\\times\\mathbb{Z}_2$. This answers an open problem proposed by Est\\'elyi and\nPisanski in 2016.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 13 Aug 2019 09:06:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-08-14"}
